    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-11-24T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-11-24T11:00:00-05:00" n="261"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d261">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 Changsha/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-24T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 24, 1930—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>402. Legation’s despatch 508, October 8.<note n="17" xml:id="d261fn17">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Department requests that Minister Johnson report by telegraph any progress
                        made in arriving at an understanding with the Chinese Government with regard
                        to (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) method of assessing claims for indemnity to
                        cover losses at Changsha and in its vicinity arising from so-called
                        communist depredations in July and August; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) method
                        of payment of such claims when assessed.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>What if any plans are being given consideration by representatives of
                        other governments in connection with Changsha losses?</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The Chinese authorities should be strongly urged to resume and make up
                        arrears in payments under the Nanking settlement.<note n="18"
                            xml:id="d261fn18">See <ref target="frus1929v02#pg_858">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 858</ref> ff.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
